 box total\n  |votes      = '''630,667'''\n  |percentage = '''100.0%'''\n  |change     = N/A\n}}\n{{Election box gain with party link no swing\n | winner = Democratic Party (United States)\n | loser  = Republican Party (United States)\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[United States gubernatorial elections, 2018]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.maine.gov/sos/cec/elec/ Maine Secretary of State \u2013 Elections Division]\n*[https://votesmart.org/election/2018/G/ME/2018-gubernatorial Candidates] at [[Vote Smart]] \n*[https://ballotpedia.org/Maine_gubernatorial_election,_2018 Candidates] at [[Ballotpedia]]\n\n; Official campaign websites\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20180119120709/http://www.capron4me.com/ Kenneth Capron (I) for Governor]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20181017165547/http://www.hayesformaine.com/ Terry Hayes (I) for Governor]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20181015183933/http://jenkinsforgovernor.org/ John Jenkins (I) for Governor]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20181031002201/http://janetmills.com/ Janet Mills (D) for Governor]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20181019220734/https://www.shawnmoody.com/ Shawn Moody (R) for Governor]\n\n{{United States elections, 2018}}\n{{US Third Party Election}}\n{{Maine elections}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Maine Gubernatorial Election, 2018}}\n[[Category:2018 Maine elections|Gubernatorial]]\n[[Category:Maine gubernatorial elections|2018]]\n[[Category:2018 United States gubernatorial elections]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox Election\n| election_name      = 2018 Maine gubernatorial election\n| country            = Maine\n| type               = presidential\n| ongoing            = no\n| previous_election  = 2014 Maine gubernatorial election\n| previous_year      = 2014\n| next_election      = 2022 Maine gubernatorial election\n| next_year          = 2022\n| election_date      = {{Start date|2018|11|6}}\n| image1             = [[File:Janet Mills in 2019.jpg|x150px]]\n| nominee1           = '''[[Janet Mills]]'''\n| party1             = Democratic Party (United States)\n| popular_vote1      = '''320,962'''\n| percentage1        = '''50.9%'''\n| image2             = [[File:No image.svg|x120px]]\n| nominee2           = Shawn Moody\n| party2             = Republican Party (United States)\n| popular_vote2      = 272,311\n| percentage2        = 43.2%\n| image3             = [[File:No image.svg|x110px]]\n| nominee3           = [[Terry Hayes (politician)|Terry Hayes]]\n| party3             = Independent (United States)\n| popular_vote3      = 37,268\n| percentage3        = 5.9%\n| map_image          = File:Maine governor election results by county, 2018.svg\n| map_size           = 200px\n| map_caption        = County results<br/>'''Mills:''' {{legend0|#a5b0ff|40-50%}} {{legend0|#7996e2|50\u201360%}} {{legend0|#6674de|60\u201370%}}<br/>'''Moody:''' {{legend0|#ffb2b2|40\u201350%}} {{legend0|#e27f7f|50\u201360%}} \n| title              = Governor\n| before_election    = [[Paul LePage]]\n| before_party       = Republican Party (United States)\n| after_election     = [[Janet T. Mills|Janet Mills]]\n| after_party        = Democratic Party (United States)\n}}\n{{ElectionsME}}\nThe '''2018 Maine gubernatorial election''' took place on November 6, 2018, to elect the next [[Governor of Maine]]. It occurred along with elections for the [[United States Senate election in Maine, 2018|U.S. Senate]], [[United States House of Representatives elections in Maine, 2018|U.S. House]], and other state and local elections. Incumbent [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] Governor [[Paul LePage]] was term limited and could not seek reelection to a third consecutive term in office.\n\nThe primaries for this election were the first in Maine to be conducted with [[ranked choice voting]] (RCV), as opposed to a simple plurality, after voters passed [[Maine Question 5, 2016|a citizen referendum]] approving the change in 2016.<ref>{{cite news|title=Maine became the first state in the country Tuesday to pass ranked choice voting|url=https://www.boston.com/news/politics/2016/11/10/maine-became-the-first-state-in-the-country-to-pass-ranked-choice-voting|accessdate=November 17, 2016|newspaper=Boston Globe|date=November 10, 2016}}</ref> An [[advisory opinion]] by the [[Maine Supreme Judicial Court]] held that RCV would be unconstitutional for general elections for governor and the state legislature. This led state legislators to vote to delay its implementation pending approval of a state constitutional amendment.<ref>{{cite news|title=Maine Supreme Judicial Court rules ranked-choice voting unconstitutional|url=http://bangordailynews.com/2017/05/23/politics/maine-supreme-judicial-court-rules-ranked-choice-voting-unconstitutional/|accessdate=May 23, 2016|newspaper=Bangor Daily News|date=May 23, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wcsh6.com/news/politics/loose-ends-bring-legislature-back-for-special-session/485282422|title=Ranked choice voting delayed until 2021|first=|last=TEGNA|publisher=}}</ref> Backers of a \"people's veto\" turned in enough signatures to suspend this law until a [[Maine Question 1, June 2018|June referendum vote]], which restored RCV for future primary and congressional elections.<ref>{{cite news|title=Voters will decide in June whether Maine keeps its ranked-choice voting law|url=https://www.pressherald.com/2018/03/05/voters-in-june-will-decide-if-maine-keeps-its-ranked-choice-voting-law/|accessdate=March 16, 2018|newspaper=Portland Press Herald|date=March 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\nGovernor [[Paul LePage]] threatened not to certify the results of the primary elections, saying he would \"leave it up to the courts to decide.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Nilsen |first=Ella |publisher=Vox |title=Maine\u2019s governor is threatening not to certify the results of Tuesday\u2019s primary |accessdate=June 13, 2018 |url=https://www.vox.com/2018/6/12/17453676/paul-lepage-maine-governor-threatening-not-to-certify-tuesday-primary-results-2018-midterms}}</ref> He also called the use of ranked-choice voting the \"most horrific thing in the world.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Levine |first=Sam |publisher=Huffington Post |title=Maine Gov. Paul LePage \u2018Probably\u2019 Won\u2019t Certify Primary Election Results |accessdate=June 13, 2018 |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/paul-lepage-ranked-choice-voting_us_5b203bf1e4b09d7a3d781600}}</ref> Secretary of State [[Matthew Dunlap]] said the results would be binding regardless of whether LePage certified them.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/06/13/republican-sanford-loses-in-south-carolina-after-trump-urges-his-ouster.html|title=Republican Sanford loses in South Carolina after Trump urges his ouster|last=|first=|date=|work=[[CNBC]]|access-date=|quote=Maine Secretary of State Matt Dunlap said the election results would be binding anyway, the Portland Press Herald said.}}</ref>\n\nThe Republican nominee was businessman and [[Maine gubernatorial election, 2010|2010 independent candidate]] for governor Shawn Moody. The Democratic candidate was [[Maine Attorney General|Attorney General]] [[Janet T. Mills|Janet Mills]]. [[Maine State Treasurer|State Treasurer]] [[Terry Hayes (politician)|Terry Hayes]] and businessman Alan Caron had qualified for the ballot as independents, though Caron dropped out on October 29 and endorsed Mills. Former state senator and former mayor of [[Lewiston, Maine|Lewiston]] and [[Auburn, Maine|Auburn]] John Jenkins and perennial candidate Kenneth Capron ran write-in campaigns.\n\nMills defeated Moody and Hayes with a majority on the first count to become the first female Governor of Maine. She also became the first gubernatorial candidate to win at least 50% of the vote since [[Angus King]] in [[Maine gubernatorial election, 1998|1998]], and the first non-incumbent to do so since [[Kenneth M. Curtis]] in [[Maine gubernatorial election, 1966|1966]]. Mills also became the first Maine gubernatorial candidate to earn 300,000 votes and received more votes for governor than any other candidate in state history.\n\n==Background==\nIncumbent Republican [[Paul LePage]] is term-limited, having been elected twice consecutively in [[Maine gubernatorial election, 2010|2010]] and [[Maine gubernatorial election, 2014|2014]]. LePage did not win a majority of the vote either time (receiving 37.6% in a crowded four-way race in 2010 and 48.2% in a three-way race in 2014), with Democrats accusing independent candidate [[Eliot Cutler]] of splitting the anti-LePage vote in both instances, though Cutler finished closer to LePage than Democratic candidate [[Libby Mitchell]] in the 2010 election.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.msnbc.com/rachel-maddow-show/republican-governors-association-exploits-its-pawn-maine|title=Republican Governors Association exploits its pawn in Maine|publisher=MSNBC|author=Steve Benen|date=October 28, 2014 |accessdate=January 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\nMaine's history of governors elected without majorities, including LePage, was one impetus for the [[Maine Question 5, 2016|citizen's referendum]] to implement [[Ranked-Choice Voting|ranked choice voting]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bangordailynews.com/2014/10/27/politics/elections/maine-lawmakers-seek-to-end-strategic-voting-spoilers-with-petition-for-ranked-choice-voting/?ref=relatedBox|title=Maine lawmakers seek to end strategic voting, 'spoilers' with petition for ranked-choice voting|publisher=Bangor Daily News |date=October 27, 2015 |accessdate=January 20, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rcvmaine.com/whats_the_problem_with_our_current_voting_system|title=What's the problem with our current voting system?|publisher=The Committee for Ranked Choice Voting |accessdate=January 29, 2018}}</ref> Indeed, the last time a gubernatorial candidate received a majority of the vote was in [[Maine gubernatorial election, 1998|1998]], when incumbent Governor (and current United States Senator) [[Angus King]], an independent, won reelection with 58.6% of the vote. The last time a non-incumbent candidate received more than 50% of the vote was the [[Maine gubernatorial election, 1966|1966 gubernatorial election]], which Democrat [[Kenneth M. Curtis]] won over incumbent Republican [[John H. Reed]] with 53.1% of the vote.\n\nThough ranked-choice voting was approved by voters in a [[Maine Question 5, 2016|2016 referendum]], the [[Maine Legislature]] voted to delay and potentially repeal RCV for all elections after an [[advisory opinion]] by the [[Maine Supreme Judicial Court]] ruled it unconstitutional for general elections for state offices. RCV supporters succeeded in a people's veto effort to prevent the delay, which suspends it until a June 2018 referendum vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pressherald.com/2018/02/02/ranked-choice-voters-submit-signatures-for-peoples-veto-ballot-initiative/|title=Ranked-choice voters submit signatures for 'people's veto' ballot initiative |date=February 2, 2018}}</ref> RCV supporters were victorious in the June referendum, and ranked-choice voting will remain in place for state and federal primaries and federal general elections.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2018/06/maine-lepage-ranked-choice-voting/562871/|title=Maine Voters Overrule Their Leaders|first=Russell|last=Berman|work=[[The Atlantic]]|date=June 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Republican primary==\nSpeculation that U.S. Senator [[Susan Collins]] was considering running for governor arose during the 2015 [[Maine Legislature|Maine Legislative]] session when Representative [[Matt Moonen]] (D-Portland) introduced a bill to strip the governor (LePage at the time) of the power to appoint replacement U.S. Senators in the event of a vacancy and to instead have a special primary and general election. Moonen denied that he was motivated by Collins's possible candidacy, saying he was interested only in counterbalancing Republican-sponsored bills to change how the [[Maine Attorney General]] and [[Maine Secretary of State]] are chosen. Moonen said Collins had told him speculation about her running for governor was \"silly.\"<ref name=collinsno>{{cite news|title=Lawmaker says his bill isn't about Susan Collins running for governor|url=http://bangordailynews.com/2015/03/30/politics/state-house/lawmaker-says-his-bill-isnt-about-susan-collins-running-for-governor/|accessdate=March 31, 2015|newspaper=Bangor Daily News|date=March 30, 2014}}</ref> Collins, who was the [[Maine gubernatorial election, 1994|1994 Republican nominee for Governor]], told [[MPBN]] News on January 4, 2016 that though she was \"baffled\" by the rumors about her being interested in running for governor, many had encouraged her to run, and she would not rule it out.<ref name=collinsmaybe>{{cite news|title=Collins Says She Is Baffled By Rumor She Is Running For Governor|url=http://news.mpbn.net/post/collins-says-she-baffled-rumor-she-running-governor|accessdate=January 4, 2016|newspaper=MPBN News|date=January 4, 2016}}</ref> In October 2017, Collins said she would not run for governor in 2018.<ref>Cook, Janet. \"[https://www.wsj.com/articles/susan-collins-to-remain-in-u-s-senate-1507900816?mod=e2tw Susan Collins to Remain in U.S. Senate]\". ''The Wall Street Journal''. October 13, 2017.</ref>\n\nNo Republican candidate ruled out challenging the results of a ranked-choice primary in court. [[Mary Mayhew]] called for the immediate repeal of RCV, calling it a \"scam\" and \"probably illegal\".<ref name=RCV>{{cite news|title=Candidates for Blaine House signal they might challenge outcome of a ranked-choice vote|url=https://www.pressherald.com/2018/04/07/candidates-for-maine-governor-signal-they-might-challenge-outcome-of-ranked-choice-vote/|accessdate=April 7, 2018|newspaper=Portland Press  Herald|date=April 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Maine Republican Party]] filed a federal lawsuit in U.S. District Court in [[Bangor, Maine|Bangor]] on May 4, 2018, seeking to bar the use of RCV for its own primary on the grounds that requiring the party to use it violates its [[First Amendment to the United States Constitution|First Amendment]] rights to choose its nominee as it sees fit.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://mainepublic.org/post/gop-files-suit-block-ranked-choice-voting |title=GOP Files Suit To Block Ranked-Choice Voting |last=Leary |first=Mal |date=May 4, 2018 |work=[[MPBN]] |access-date=May 7, 2018}}</ref> U.S. District Court Judge Jon Levy rejected the suit on May 29.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://mainepublic.org/post/judge-maine-gop-must-use-ranked-choice-voting-primary|title=Judge: Maine GOP Must Use Ranked-Choice Voting In Primary |last=Leary |first=Mal |date=May 29, 2018 |work=[[MPBN]] |access-date=May 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Candidates===\n====Nominated====\n*Shawn Moody, businessman and independent candidate for governor in [[Maine gubernatorial election, 2010|2010]]<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://bangordailynews.com/2017/11/21/politics/shawn-moody-launches-gop-gubernatorial-bid-run-by-lepage-insiders/ |title=Moody announces GOP gubernatorial bid run by LePage insiders |last=Shepherd |first=Michael |date=November 21, 2017 |work=[[Bangor Daily News]] |access-date=November 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Eliminated in primary====\n* [[Kenneth Fredette|Ken Fredette]], State House Minority Leader<ref>{{cite news|title=Maine House Minority Leader Fredette announces he's running for governor|url=http://www.pressherald.com/2017/09/06/maine-house-minority-leader-fredette-to-announce-campaign-for-governors-office/|accessdate=September 6, 2017|newspaper=Portland Press Herald|date=September 6, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Garrett Mason]], State Senate Majority Leader<ref>{{cite news|title=Republican Garrett Mason to announce gubernatorial bid this week|url=https://bangordailynews.com/2017/09/05/politics/republican-garrett-mason-to-announce-maine-gubernatorial-run-wednesday/|accessdate=September 6, 2017|newspaper=Bangor Daily News|date=September 5, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Mary Mayhew]], former commissioner of the Maine Department of Health and Human Services<ref name=\"BDN6617\">{{cite news|url=http://bangordailynews.com/2017/06/06/politics/mary-mayhew-launches-campaign-to-replace-lepage-in-2018/|title=Mary Mayhew launches campaign to replace LePage in 2018|last=Shepherd|first=Michael|date=June 6, 2017|work=[[Bangor Daily News]]|accessdate=June 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Withdrawn====\n* Deril Stubenrod, write-in candidate for the U.S. Senate in [[United States Senate election in Maine, 2014|2014]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://stateandcapitol.bangordailynews.com/2017/02/03/meet-maines-first-2018-gubernatorial-candidate-but-dont-expect-him-to-win/|title=Meet Maine\u2019s first 2018 gubernatorial candidate, but don\u2019t expect him to win|work=[[Bangor Daily News]]|last=Shepherd|first=Michael|date=February 3, 2017|accessdate=February 3, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Mike Thibodeau]], Maine Senate President<ref>{{cite news|url=http://bangordailynews.com/2018/03/26/politics/maine-senate-president-mike-thibodeau-quits-gop-race-to-succeed-lepage/|title=Maine Senate President Mike Thibodeau quits GOP race to succeed LePage|work=[[Bangor Daily News]]|last=Shepherd|first=Michael|date=March 26, 2018|accessdate=March 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Declined====\n* [[Richard A. Bennett|Rick Bennett]], former chairman of the [[Maine Republican Party]], former [[List of Presidents of the Maine Senate|President]] of the [[Maine Senate]], candidate for the U.S. Senate in [[United States Senate election in Maine, 2012|2012]] and nominee for [[Maine's 2nd congressional district|ME-02]] in [[United States House of Representatives elections, 1994|1994]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wcsh6.com/news/politics/bennett-wont-run-for-governor/466519090|title=Bennett won't run for governor|first=|last=TEGNA|publisher=}}</ref>\n* [[Susan Collins]], U.S. Senator and nominee for governor in [[Maine gubernatorial election, 1994|1994]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Is Susan Collins planning to run for governor in 2018?|url=http://bangordailynews.com/2015/03/13/politics/will-susan-collins-seek-gubernatorial-bid-in-2018-democrats-bill-could-be-a-sign/?ref=comments|accessdate=March 14, 2015|newspaper=Bangor Daily News|date=March 13, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2017/10/13/collins-no-run-for-maine-governor-243747|title= Collins declines run for Maine governor|last=Strauss|first=Daniel|date=October 13, 2017|work=[[Politico]]|accessdate= October 13, 2017}}</ref>\n* Nick Isgro, Mayor of [[Waterville, Maine|Waterville]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.centralmaine.com/2018/01/29/waterville-mayor-nick-isgro-not-running-for-governor-but-criticizes-gop-candidates/|title=Waterville Mayor Nick Isgro considering run for governor|work=[[Morning Sentinel]]|last=Calder|first=Amy|date=January 29, 2018|accessdate=January 30, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Bruce Poliquin]], U.S. Representative (ran for reelection)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/news/politics/2018/02/10/democrats-seek-wipe-out-last-gop-house-member-new-england/foLtPeeoDo9CZErg7vgCPO/story.html|title=Democrats seek to wipe out the last GOP House member in New England - The Boston Globe|publisher=|accessdate=May 22, 2018}}</ref>\n* Peter Vigue, businessman<ref name=jockey>{{cite news|url=http://bangordailynews.com/2016/12/18/the-point/whos-jockeying-for-a-head-start-in-the-race-to-become-maines-next-governor/|title=Who's jockeying for a head start in the race to become Maine's next governor?|work=[[Bangor Daily News]]|last=Shepherd|first=Michael|date=December 18, 2016|accessdate=December 18, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Endorsements===\n{{Endorsements box\n| title = Ken Fredette\n| list =\n; Federal politicians\n* [[Marco Rubio]], United States Senator from Florida and 2016 presidential candidate<ref>{{Cite tweet |number=946186395869175808 |user=KenFredetteME |title=Proud to have the endorsement of Senator @marcorubio. And thank you Sen. Rubio for your vote on the tax refo