ted States House of Representatives elections in Maine, 2016|2016]]<ref name=mills /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://secure.mainecampaignfinance.com/PublicSite/SearchPages/CommitteeDetail.aspx?OrgID=10113 |title=Candidate and Committee Information for Dresser, Jay Parker Lunt |date=December 28, 2017 |website=Maine Commission on Governmental Ethics and Election Practices |access-date=January 18, 2018}}</ref>\n* Betsy Marsano, activist<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stateandcapitol.bangordailynews.com/2017/07/24/democrats-might-have-found-the-mainer-they-want-to-challenge-poliquin/|title=Democrats might have found the Mainer they want to challenge Poliquin|date=July 24, 2017|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://stateandcapitol.bangordailynews.com/2018/02/27/lesson-one-from-gop-debate-its-still-all-about-lepage/ |title=Lesson One from GOP debate: It's still all about LePage |last=Cousins |first=Christopher |date=February 27, 2018 |work=[[Bangor Daily News]] |access-date=February 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Libertarian primary==\n\n===Candidates===\n\n====Withdrawn====\n* Richard Light<ref name=\"Shepherd\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://secure.mainecampaignfinance.com/PublicSite/SearchPages/CommitteeDetail.aspx?OrgID=10066 |title=Candidate/Committee Information for Light, Richard |date=January 3, 2018 |website=Maine Commission on Governmental Ethics and Election Practices |access-date=January 18, 2018}}</ref>\n* Gilbert P. Doughty<ref>{{cite web |url=https://secure.mainecampaignfinance.com/PublicSite/SearchPages/CommitteeDetail.aspx?OrgID=10350 |title=Candidate/Committee Information for Doughty, Gilbert P. |date=January 12, 2018 |website=Maine Commission on Governmental Ethics and Election Practices |access-date=January 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Independents==\n===Candidates===\n====Declared====\n* Kenneth A. Capron, perennial candidate, systems analyst and fraud investigator<ref>{{cite web |url=https://secure.mainecampaignfinance.com/#/exploreDetails/5723/10/null/32/2018 |title=Candidate/Committee Information for Capron, Kenneth A, |date=November 27, 2017 |website=Maine Commission on Governmental Ethics and Election Practices |access-date=January 18, 2018}}</ref>{{note|id1||}}(write-in candidate)\n* [[Terry Hayes (politician)|Terry Hayes]], [[Maine State Treasurer]]<ref name=hayes/>\n* [[John Jenkins (American politician)|John Jenkins]], former mayor of [[Lewiston, Maine|Lewiston]], former mayor of [[Auburn, Maine|Auburn]] and former Democratic state senator<ref>{{cite news|title=John Jenkins eyeing possible gubernatorial race|url=http://www.sunjournal.com/news/maine/2017/09/01/john-jenkins-eyeing-possible-gubernatorial-race/2193172|accessdate=September 1, 2017|newspaper=Lewiston Sun Journal|date=September 1, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Former mayor of both Lewiston and Auburn files to run for governor|url=http://www.pressherald.com/2017/11/16/former-mayor-of-both-lewiston-and-auburn-files-for-2018-governors-race/|accessdate=November 18, 2017|newspaper=Portland Press Herald|date=November 18, 2017}}</ref>{{note|id3||}}(write-in candidate)\n\n<small>{{note label|id4||none}}Capron and Jenkins failed to qualify for the ballot, but continued their campaigns as write-in candidates</small>\n\n====Withdrawn====\n* Ethan Alcorn, businessman (did not qualify)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://secure.mainecampaignfinance.com/#/exploreDetails/5718/10/null/32/2018|title=Maine Ethics Commission}}</ref>\n*Alan Caron, president and CEO of Envision Maine (endorsed Mills)<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.pressherald.com/2017/09/11/alan-caron-may-be-next-to-enter-2018-governors-race/|title=Alan Caron may be next to enter 2018 governor\u2019s race|date=September 11, 2017|newspaper=Portland Press Herald|accessdate=September 11, 2017}}</ref>\n* Aaron D. Chadbourne, writer and activist<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://secure.mainecampaignfinance.com/#/exploreDetails/6253/10/null/32/2018 |title=Filings for Mr Aaron D. Chadbourne |date=June 14, 2018 |website=Maine Commission on Governmental Ethics and Election Practices |access-date=June 26, 2018}}</ref> (write-in candidate, endorsed Moody)<ref name=\"Chadbourne\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/notes/run-aaron-run/ending-the-campaign-beginning-a-new-chapter/227862021243221/ |title=Ending the Campaign; Beginning a New Chapter |last=Chadbourne |first=Aaron |date=September 4, 2018 |website=[[Facebook]] |access-date=October 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Failed to make ballot====\n* Karmo Sanders, actress<ref>{{cite news|title=No joke: Karmo Sanders, the 'Marden's Lady,' wants to run for governor|url=http://www.centralmaine.com/2017/06/02/no-joke-karmo-sanders-the-mardens-lady-wants-to-run-for-governor|accessdate=June 2, 2017|newspaper=MPBN News|date=June 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Declined====\n* [[Eliot Cutler]], attorney and candidate for governor in [[Maine gubernatorial election, 2010|2010]] and [[Maine gubernatorial election, 2014|2014]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pressherald.com/2015/04/02/would-cutler-run-for-governor-again-no-ive-taken-a-vow/|title=Would Eliot Cutler run for governor again? 'No, I've taken a vow' |publisher=Portland Press Herald |author=Whit Richardson |date=April 2, 2015 |accessdate=April 2, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Angus King]], U.S. Senator and former governor ([[United States Senate election in Maine, 2018|running for re-election]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mainepublic.org/post/lepage-steps-criticism-sen-angus-king#stream/0|title=LePage Steps up Criticism of Sen. Angus King|work=[[Maine Public Broadcasting Network]]|last=Mistler|first=Steve|date=November 11, 2016|accessdate=November 17, 2016}}</ref>\n* Peter Vigue, businessman<ref name=who>{{cite news|title=Who will run for governor in 2018?|url=http://leftbrainrightbrain.bangordailynews.com/2016/11/17/home/who-will-run-for-governor-in-2018/|accessdate=November 17, 2016|newspaper=Bangor Daily News|date=November 17, 2016}}</ref><ref name=jockey />\n* [[Richard Woodbury|Dick Woodbury]], former state senator<ref name=jockey />\n\n== General election ==\nAfter the primaries, most prediction models had the race as a tossup, noting Paul LePage's two victories and [[Hillary Clinton]]'s narrow margin of victory in the state in the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 presidential election]]. Others considered it to be a pick-up opportunity for the Democrats.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2018/10/10/governors-seats-most-likely-flip-parties-november/?noredirect=on |title=The 10 governor's seats most likely to flip parties in November |last=Phillips |first=Amber |date=October 10, 2018 |website=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=October 13, 2018}}</ref> Both Moody and Mills received the backing of outside money, with one PAC spending in excess of $1 million on television advertising in the state to support Mills's candidacy.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.pressherald.com/2018/09/17/democratic-pac-tops-1-million-in-spending-in-governors-race/ |title=Democratic PAC tops $1 million in spending in Maine governor\u2019s race |last=Gallagher |first=Noel K. |date=September 17, 2018 |work=[[The Portland Press Herald]] |access-date=October 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn October 12, [[Jonathan Martin (journalist)|Jonathan Martin]] of the ''[[New York Times]]'' published an article detailing a sex discrimination complaint filed against Moody and his business in 2006, which Moody settled for $20,000, resulting in the complaint being withdrawn. The complaint alleged that Moody went to the residence of a female employee and fired her for having a child just days after delivering the child via an emergency [[caesarean section]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/12/us/politics/shawn-moody-maine-discrimination.html |title=He Settled a Sex Discrimination Complaint. Now He Wants to Lead Maine. |last=Martin |first=Jonathan |date=October 12, 2018 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=October 13, 2018}}</ref> Moody denied the allegation through a spokesperson and later on Twitter.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.wmtw.com/article/moody-responds-to-sex-discrimination-allegation-printed-in-new-york-times/23734297 |title=Moody responds to sex discrimination allegation printed in New York Times |last=Merrill |first=Paul |date=October 12, 2018 |work=[[WMTW-TV]] |access-date=October 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThough the first poll of the race saw Mills and Moody tied for first place with Hayes and Caron lagging behind, by the end of October, four different polls were released, each showing Mills with an eight-point lead over Moody. [[FiveThirtyEight]] declared the race \"Likely D\" when its gubernatorial projections were released in October, though other prediction models maintained the race as a tossup.\n\nOn October 29, in a press conference at the main branch of the [[Portland Public Library]], Caron dropped out of the race and endorsed Mills. His name remained on the ballot, but any votes cast for him were regarded as blank.<ref name=\"CaronEndorse\">{{Cite news|url=https://bangordailynews.com/2018/10/29/politics/independent-alan-caron-quits-maine-governors-race/|title=Independent Alan Caron quits Maine governor\u2019s race|last=Shepherd|first=Michael|date=October 29, 2018|work=[[Bangor Daily News]]|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nShortly before 10 PM on election night, Hayes conceded the race.<ref name=\"MainePublic\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.mainepublic.org/post/live-updates-democrat-janet-mills-becomes-maines-next-governor#stream/0 |title=Live Updates: Democrat Janet Mills Becomes Maine's Next Governor |date=November 6, 2018 |website=MainePublic.org}}</ref> At 12:15 AM on November 7, Moody conceded the race to Mills, and shortly thereafter Mills declared victory at Democratic headquarters in Portland.<ref name=\"MainePublic\"/> Mills became the first Maine gubernatorial candidate to receive more than 300,000 votes in a single election. Mills also became the first Maine gubernatorial candidate to win a majority of the vote since [[Angus King]] won nearly 59% of the vote in his re-election bid in [[Maine gubernatorial election, 1998|1998]], and became the first candidate to win a majority of the popular vote for a first term since [[Kenneth M. Curtis]] defeated incumbent governor [[John H. Reed]] in [[Maine gubernatorial election, 1966|1966]], though Curtis and Reed were the only candidates in that race.\n\nThe general election used [[plurality voting]], not [[Instant-runoff voting|ranked-choice voting]].\n\n=== Predictions ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Source\n!Ranking\n!As of\n|-\n|[[The Cook Political Report]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cookpolitical.com/ratings/governor-race-ratings|title=2018 Governor Race ratings {{!}} The Cook Political Report|website=The Cook Political Report|language=en|access-date=November 15, 2017}}</ref>\n|{{sort|100|Tossup}}\n|January 26, 2018\n|-\n|[[Inside Elections]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://insideelections.com/ratings/governor/2018-gubernatorial-ratings-september-14-2018|title=Gubernatorial Ratings {{!}} Inside Elections|website=insideelections.com|language=en|access-date=2018-09-18}}</ref>\n| style=\"background:#ddf\" |{{sort|098|Tilt D}}\n|September 14, 2018\n|-\n|[[Sabato's Crystal Ball]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.centerforpolitics.org/crystalball/2018-governor/|title=Larry J. Sabato's Crystal Ball  \u00bb 2018 Governor|website=www.centerforpolitics.org|language=en-US|access-date=November 15, 2017}}</ref>\n| style=\"background:#ccf\" |{{sort|100|Lean D}}\n|November 5, 2018\n|-\n|[[RealClearPolitics]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.realclearpolitics.com/epolls/2018/governor/2018_elections_governor_map.html|title=2018 Governor Races|website=[[RealClearPolitics]]|date=October 9, 2018}}</ref>\n| style=\"background:#ccf\" |{{sort|098|Lean D}}\n|October 9, 2018\n|-\n|[[Daily Kos]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailykos.com/stories/2018/6/4/1769407/-Daily-Kos-Elections-2018-race-ratings|title=Daily Kos Elections 2018 race ratings|website