inger-dead-at-57-w446467|website=Rolling Stone|accessdate=11 November 2016}}</ref>\n*'''24''' \u2013 [[Bobby Vee]] (73) American pop singer who was a teen idol in the early 1960s\n*'''30''' \u2013 [[Curly Putman]], (85), American singer-songwriter. [[D-I-V-O-R-C-E]], [[Green, Green Grass of Home]] and the subject of [[Paul McCartney]] & Wings song [[Junior's Farm]].\n\n===November===\n*'''1'''\n**[[Nico Carstens]] (90), South African accordionist and songwriter<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.channel24.co.za/Music/News/accordion-maestro-nico-carstens-dies-20161102|date=2016-11-02|title=Accordion Maestro Nico Carstens Dies|publisher=Channel 24}}</ref>\n**[[Pocho La Pantera]] (65), [[Argentine cumbia]] singer\n*'''3''' \u2013 [[Kay Starr]] (94), American pop and jazz singer, complications of Alzheimer's disease.\n*'''4'''\n** [[Eddie Harsch]], 59, Canadian keyboardist ([[The Black Crowes]])\n** [[Jean-Jacques Perrey]], 87, French electronic music producer\n*'''7''' \u2013 [[Leonard Cohen]] (82), Canadian singer-songwriter<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gehr|first1=Richard|title=Leonard Cohen Dead at 82|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/leonard-cohen-dead-at-82-w449792|website=Rolling Stone|accessdate=11 November 2016}}</ref>\n*'''11'''\n** [[Victor Bailey (musician)|Victor Bailey]] (56), American jazz bass guitarist\n** [[Esma Red\u017eepova|Esma Red\u017eepova-Teodosievska]], (73), Macedonian vocalist, songwriter, and humanitarian of Romani ethnicity.\n* '''12''' \u2013 [[Jacques Werup]] (71), Swedish musician and writer.<ref>[http://www.aftonbladet.se/nojesbladet/article23902109.ab Jacques Werup d\u00f6d] {{in lang|sv}}</ref>\n*'''13''' \u2013 [[Leon Russell]] (74), American musician and songwriter\n*'''15'''\n** [[Holly Dunn]] (59), American country singer-songwriter\n** [[Mose Allison]] (89), American pianist and singer.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://jazztimes.com/articles/172684-mose-allison-dies-at-89 | title=Mose Allison Dies at 89 | publisher=[[JazzTimes]] | date=2016-11-15 | accessdate=2016-12-05}}</ref>\n*'''18''' \u2013 [[Sharon Jones (singer)|Sharon Jones]] (60), American soul and funk singer\n*'''24''' \u2013 [[Pauline Oliveros]] (84), American composer\n*'''29''' \u2013 [[Allan Zavod]] (71), Australian keyboardist and composer\n*'''30''' \u2013 [[Ivar Thomassen]] (62), Norwegian folk singer, songwriter, and jazz pianist.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.altaposten.no/kultur/2016/11/30/%E2%80%93-En-av-de-store-er-g%C3%A5tt-bort-13864429.ece |title= En av de store er g\u00e5tt bort |language=no |first= Rolf Edmund |last=Lund |newspaper= [[Altaposten]] |date= 30 November 2016 |accessdate= 2016-12-05}}</ref>\n\n===December===\n*'''2''' \u2013 [[Mark Gray (singer)|Mark Gray]] (64), American singer-songwriter ([[Exile (American band)|Exile]])\n*'''4''' \u2013 Ralph Johnson (67), American singer ([[The Impressions]])\n*'''8'''\n** [[Greg Lake]] (69), English progressive-rock vocalist and multi-instrumentalist<ref>[https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/greg-lake-emerson-lake-palmer-co-founder-dead-at-69-w454546 Greg Lake, Emerson, Lake & Palmer Co-Founder, Dead at 69 \u2013 Rolling Stone<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n** [[Junaid Jamshed]] (52), Pakistani singer-songwriter ([[Vital Signs (pop band)|Vital Signs]]), flight collision<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/dec/07/pakistan-plane-crashes-flight-pk661 Pop star Junaid Jamshed among 48 killed in Pakistan plane crash | World news | The Guardian<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n*'''11''' \u2013 Joe Ligon (80), American gospel singer ([[Mighty Clouds of Joy]])\n*'''24''' \u2013 [[Rick Parfitt]] (68), English musician and songwriter ([[Status Quo (band)|Status Quo]])<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-28640835 Obituary: Rick Parfitt \u2013 BBC News<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n*'''25''' \u2013 [[George Michael]] (53), English singer-songwriter ([[Wham!]]) <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-38432862 |title=Ex-Wham singer George Michael dies |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=25 December 2016 |accessdate=25 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Music}}\n* [[Timeline of musical events]]\n* [[Women in music]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:2016 in music| ]]\n[[Category:2016-related lists]]\n[[Category:Music by year]]\n", "name_user": "Alaney2k", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eJanuary:the work's name is \"The New York Times\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2016_in_music"}
{"title_page": "2016 Slovak parliamentary election", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name = 2016 Slovak parliamentary election\n| country = Slovakia\n| type = parliamentary\n| ongoing = no\n| previous_election = 2012 Slovak parliamentary election\n| previous_year = 2012\n| next_election = 2020 Slovak parliamentary election\n| next_year = 2020\n| seats_for_election = All 150 seats in the [[National Council (Slovakia)|National Council]]\n| majority_seats = 76\n| election_date = 5 March 2016\n| turnout = 2,648,184 (59.82%)<br>{{increase}} 0.71 pp\n\n<!-- SMER-SD -->| image1 = [[File:Fico Juncker (cropped).jpg|120x120px]]\n| leader1 = [[Robert Fico]]\n| party1 = Direction \u2013 Social Democracy\n| leader_since1 = 1999\n| last_election1 = 83 seats, 44.4%\n| seats1 = 49\n| seat_change1 = {{decrease}} 34\n| popular_vote1 = \n| percentage1 = 28.3%\n| swing1 = {{decrease}} 16.1 pp\n\n<!-- SaS -->| image2 = [[File:Richard Sul\u00edk -2011-.jpg|120x120px]]\n| leader2 = [[Richard Sul\u00edk]]\n| party2 = Freedom and Solidarity\n| leader_since2 = 2009\n| last_election2 = 11 seats, 5.9%\n| seats2 = 21\n| seat_change2 = {{increase}} 10\n| popular_vote2 = \n| percentage2 = 12.1%\n| swing2 = {{increase}} 6.2 pp\n\n<!-- O\u013daNO -->| image3 = \n| leader3 = [[Igor Matovi\u010d]]\n| colour3 = 485159\n| party3 = [[Ordinary People (Slovakia)|O\u013daNO\u2013NOVA]]\n| leader_since3 = 2011\n| last_election3 = 16 seats, 8.5%\n| seats3 = 19\n| seat_change3 = {{increase}} 3\n| popular_vote3 = \n| percentage3 = 11.0%\n| swing3 = {{increase}} 2.5 pp\n\n<!-- SNS -->| image4 = [[File:Andrej Danko.jpg|120x120px]]\n| leader4 = [[Andrej Danko (politician)|Andrej Danko]]\n| party4 = Slovak National Party\n| leader_since4 = 2012\n| last_election4 = 0 seats, 4.5%\n| seats4 = 15\n| seat_change4 = {{increase}} 15\n| popular_vote4 = \n| percentage4 = 8.6%\n| swing4 = {{increase}} 4.1 pp\n\n<!-- \u013dSNS -->| image5 = [[File:Marian Kotleba.jpg|120x120px]]\n| leader5 = [[Marian Kotleba]]\n| party5 = People's Party \u2013 Our Slovakia\n| leader_since5 = 2010\n| last_election5 = 0 seats, 1.6%\n| seats5 = 14\n| seat_change5 = {{increase}} 14\n| popular_vote5 = \n| percentage5 = 8.0%\n| swing5 = {{increase}} 6.4 pp\n\n<!-- Sme Rodina -->| image6 = \n| leader6 = [[Boris Koll\u00e1r]]\n| party6 = We Are Family (Slovakia)\n| leader_since6 = 2015\n| last_election6 = ''New party''\n| seats6 = 11\n| seat_change6 = ''New party''\n| popular_vote6 = \n| percentage6 = 6.6%\n| swing6 = ''New party''\n\n<!-- Most-H\u00edd -->| image7 = [[File:B\u00e9la Bug\u00e1r.jpg|120x120px]]\n| leader7 = [[B\u00e9la Bug\u00e1r]]\n| party7 = Most\u2013H\u00edd\n| leader_since7 = 2009\n| last_election7 = 13 seats, 6.9%\n| seats7 = 11\n| seat_change7 = {{decrease}} 2\n| popular_vote7 = \n| percentage7 = 6.5%\n| swing7 = {{decrease}} 0.4 pp\n\n<!-- SIE\u0164 -->| image8 = [[File:Radoslav prochazka zupny pohar na bicykli detom 2013 crop.jpg|120x120px]]\n| leader8 = [[Radoslav Proch\u00e1zka]]\n| party8 = Network (Slovak party)\n| leader_since8 = 2014\n| last_election8 = ''New party''\n| seats8 = 10\n| seat_change8 = ''New party''\n| popular_vote8 = \n| percentage8 = 5.6%\n| swing8 = ''New party''\n\n<!-- map -->| map_image = File:2016 Slovak legislative election - Vote Strength.svg\n| map_size = 400px\n| map_caption = Results of the election, showing vote strength by district.\n| title = [[Prime Minister of Slovakia|Prime Minister]]\n| posttitle = [[Prime Minister of Slovakia|Prime Minister]]\n| before_election = [[Robert Fico]]\n| before_colour = \n| after_election = [[Robert Fico]]\n| after_colour = \n| before_party = Direction \u2013 Social Democracy\n| after_party = Direction \u2013 Social Democracy\n| elected_members = [[List of members of the National Council of Slovakia, 2016\u2013|elected members]]\n| outgoing_members = [[List of members of the National Council of Slovakia (2012\u201316)|outgoing members]]\n}}\n\n'''Parliamentary elections''' were held in [[Slovakia]] on 5 March 2016 to elect the 150 members of the [[National Council of the Slovak Republic|National Council]]. The ruling left-wing populist [[Direction \u2013 Social Democracy]] (SMER\u2013SD) party remained the strongest party, but lost its majority. The [[Slovak Democratic and Christian Union \u2013 Democratic Party]] (SDK\u00da-DS) which led the government between 2000\u201306 and 2010\u201312 was defeated heavily, failing to cross the electoral threshold and losing its representation in the National Council. The centre-right [[Christian Democratic Movement]] (KDH) also failed to cross the threshold for the first time since 1990, whilst the far-right nationalist [[Kotleba \u2013 People's Party Our Slovakia]] (\u013dSNS) entered parliament for the first time.\n\n==Electoral system==\nThe 150 members of the [[National Council of the Slovak Republic|National Council]] were elected by [[proportional representation]] in a single nationwide constituency with an [[electoral threshold]] of 5% for single parties, 7% for coalitions grouping at least two parties. The elections used the [[open list]] system, with seats allocated using the [[Hagenbach-Bischoff system]]. Voters were able to cast up to four preferential votes for candidates on the list of the party they voted for.<ref>{{cite web|title=Slovakia N\u00e1rodn\u00e1 rada (National Council) Electoral System|url=http://www.ipu.org/parline-e/reports/2285_B.htm|publisher=[[Inter-Parliamentary Union]]|accessdate=8 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nAll participating parties had to register 90 days before election day and pay a [[deposit (politics)|deposit]] of \u20ac17,000, which was refunded to all parties gaining 2% or more of the vote. All Slovak citizens were allowed to vote except for [[Prisons in Slovakia|convicted felons]] in prison (only those who were convicted for serious offences), people declared ineligible to perform legal acts (legally insane) by court and citizens under 18 years of age. All citizens, who are 21 years of age or older and are permanent residents of Slovakia, were allowed to run as candidates except for [[Prisons in Slovakia|prisoners]], convicted felons and those declared ineligible to perform legal acts (legally insane) by court.<ref>{{cite news |date=9 October 2015 |title=Prieskum: Vo\u013eby by vyhral Smer, O\u013daNO-NOVA mimo parlamentu\n|url=http://spravy.pravda.sk/domace/clanok/370210-prieskum-volby-by-vyhral-smer-so-ziskom-40-olano-nova-mimo-parlamentu/ |language=Slovak |newspaper=[[Pravda (Slovakia)|Pravda]]|access-date=13 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nVoters not present in their electoral district at the time of the elections were allowed to request a [[Voter registration|voting certificate]] (''voli\u010dsk\u00fd preukaz''), which allowed them to vote in any district regardless of their residency.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Hlasovac\u00ed preukaz, Ministerstvo vn\u00fatra SR - Verejn\u00e1 spr\u00e1va|url = http://www.minv.sk/?nr16-preukaz|language=Slovak|publisher=Ministry of the Interior|accessdate = 14 December 2015}}</ref> Voters not in Slovakia on election day were allowed to request a [[Postal voting|postal vote]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Vo\u013eba po\u0161tou, Ministerstvo vn\u00fatra SR - Verejn\u00e1 spr\u00e1va|url = http://www.minv.sk/?nr16-posta|language=Slovak|publisher=Ministry of the Interior|accessdate = 14 December 2015}}</ref> According to the Central Election Committee, approx. 20,000 Slovak citizens abroad have requested a postal vote - the deadline for requests passed on 15 January 2016.\n\n==Campaign==\nThe election date was announced on 12 November 2015.<ref>{{cite news |date=12 November 2015|first=Igor|last=Stup\u0148an|title=Prieskum: Vo\u013eby do N\u00e1rodnej rady sa bud\u00fa kona\u0165 5. marca 2016 |url=http://spravy.pravda.sk/domace/clanok/373630-volby-den-d-ma-byt-5-marec/ |language=Slovak |newspaper=[[Pravda (Slovakia)|Pravda]]|access-date=12 November 2015}}</ref> On 7 December 2015, the Ministry of Interior published a list of 23 parties that registered to take part in the elections.<ref>{{cite web|title=Zoznam politick\u00fdch subjektov, ktor\u00e9 podali kandid\u00e1tnu listinu|url=http://www.minv.sk/?nr16_kandidati1|publisher=Ministry of the Interior|accessdate=8 March 2016|language=Slovak}}</ref>\n\nThe backdrop of the campaign was centered on the [[European migrant crisis]], with the governing SMER\u2013SD taking an anti-migrant stance into the election.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Germanova|first1=Miroslava|title=Slovakia\u2019s Governing Party Loses Majority as Far Right Makes Gains|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/03/07/world/europe/ruling-party-in-slovakia-loses-majority-in-elections.html?_r=0|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=8 March 2016|date=6 March 2016}}</ref> Teacher and nursing strikes occurring at the start of the year also had a negative effect on public opinion.<ref name=pol>{{cite news|last1=Cunningham|first1=Benjamin|title=5 takeaways from Slovakia\u2019s election|url=http://www.politico.eu/article/slovakia-fico-asylum-migrants-elections-nazi-nationalists/|work=[[Politico]]|accessdate=8 March 2016|date=7 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Opinion polls==\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:90%; line-height:16px;\"\n|- style=\"height:42px; background-color:#E9E9E9\"\n!style=\"width:150px;\" rowspan=\"2\"|Date\n!style=\"width:165px;\" rowspan=\"2\"|Polling firm\n!style=\"width:80px;\" rowspan=\"2\"|Sample size\n![[Direction \u2013 Social Democracy|<span style=\"font-size:95%;\">Smer\u2013SD</span>]]\n![[NETWORK (Slovak party)|<span style=\"font-size:95%;\">SIE\u0164</span>]]\n![[Christian Democratic Movement|<span style=\"font-size:95%;\">KDH</span>]]\n![[Most\u2013H\u00edd|<span style=\"font-size:95%;\">Most\u2013H\u00edd</span>]]\n![[Ordinary People (Slovakia)|<span style=\"font-size:95%;\">O\u013daNO</span>]] \n![[Slovak National Party|<span style=\"font-size:95%;\">SNS</span>]]\n![[Party of the Hungarian Community|<span style=\"fo