(Slovakia)|O\u013daNO]]</small>\n|1.6%\n|13.0%\n| style=\"background:#DC241F; color:white;\" |17.5%\n|-\n|11-14 Jan\n|AKO<ref>{{Cite web|title = PRIESKUM: Do parlamentu by sa dostalo sedem str\u00e1n, KDH by pre\u0161lo tesne|url = http://www.teraz.sk/slovensko/do-parlamentu-by-sa-dostalo-sedem-stran/176491-clanok.html|website = Teraz.sk|language=Slovak|date=15 January 2016|accessdate = 16 January 2016}}</ref>\n|1,000\n| style=\"background:#F8C1BE\" |'''40.7%'''\n|8.1%\n|5.6%\n|7.9%\n|5.7%\n|7.4%\n|{{N/A}}\n|6.2%\n|<small>w.[[Ordinary People (Slovakia)|O\u013daNO]]</small>\n|{{N/A}}\n|18.4%\n| style=\"background:#DC241F; color:white;\" |33.9%\n|-\n|colspan=\"15\" style=\"background:#D0D0D0; color:black\" | 2016\n|-\n|-|- style=\"background:#EFEFEF; font-weight:bold;\"\n| 10 Mar 2012\n| [[2012 Slovak parliamentary election|2012 elections]] <ref name=wash>{{cite news|last1=Haughton|first1=Tim|last2=Malova|first2=Darina|last3=Deegan-Krause|first3=Kevin|title=Slovakia\u2019s newly elected parliament is dramatically different and pretty much the same. Here\u2019s how.|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/monkey-cage/wp/2016/03/09/slovakias-newly-elected-parliament-is-dramatically-different-and-pretty-much-the-same-heres-how/|accessdate=9 March 2016|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=9 March 2016}}</ref>\n| 2,553,726\n| style=\"background:#F9C8CA\"| '''44.4%'''\n| style=\"background:#D0D0D0; width:1px;\" rowspan=\"1\"|<small>''Did not exist''</small>\n| 8.8%\n| 6.9%\n| 8.6%\n| 4.6%\n| 4.3%\n| 5.9%\n| style=\"background:#D0D0D0; width:1px;\" rowspan=\"1\"|<small>''Did not exist''</small>\n| 6.1%\n| 10.0%\n| style=\"background:#DF1A22; color:white;\"| 35.6%\n|}\n\n==Results==\n[[File:2016 Slovak legislative election - Vote Strength by Party.svg|thumb|Results of the election, showing vote strength for each party by district.]]\nEight parties passed the 5% threshold to win seats; [[Direction \u2013 Social Democracy]] (SMER\u2013SD) lost 34 seats, losing its majority in the National Council, but remained the largest party with 49 seats. [[Freedom and Solidarity]] (SaS) became the second party with 21 seats and [[Ordinary People (Slovakia)|Ordinary People]] (O\u013dANO\u2013NOVA) third with 19 seats.<ref name=pol/> Both performed better than their predicted pre-election polls, by distancing themselves from the previous government.<ref name=wash/><ref name=lse>{{cite web|last1=Kral|first1=Daniel|title=Slovakia\u2019s election: A party system entering uncharted waters|url=http://blogs.lse.ac.uk/europpblog/2016/03/09/slovakias-election-a-party-system-entering-uncharted-waters/|publisher=[[London School of Economics]]|accessdate=9 March 2016|date=9 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Christian Democratic Movement]] (KDH) performed poorly, losing all 16 of their seats. They just failed to cross the 5 percent threshold required for parliamentary representation, for the first time since the establishment of an independent Slovakia in 1993. The far-right nationalist [[Slovak National Party]] (SNS) and [[Kotleba \u2013 People's Party Our Slovakia]] (\u013dSNS) parties entered parliament with 8.6 percent (15 seats) and 8.0 percent (14 seats) of the vote respectively.<ref name=pol/> According to an exit poll, dissatisfaction with corruption and social issues led many to vote for \u013dSNS.<ref name=lse/>\n\nOther parties who gained representation in parliament include [[Most\u2013H\u00edd]], [[We Are Family (Slovakia)|We Are Family]], and [[Network (Slovak party)|Network]] (the latter two being new parties with their first ever representation in parliament).<ref name=result>{{cite web|title=Final Results|url=https://volbysr.sk/en/data03.html|publisher=Slovakia Statistical Office|accessdate=9 March 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160310083500/https://volbysr.sk/en/data03.html|archivedate=10 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Overall voter turnout was 59.8 percent.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://volbysr.sk/en/data01.html |title=The Election to the National Council of SR 2016: Final results |publisher=Statistical Office of the Slovak Republic |accessdate=10 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nTwelve of the 150 MPs were elected due to preferential voting despite being initially placed further down their party list than the number of seats won by their party; 7 out of 19 for O\u013dANO\u2013NOVA, one out of 14 for Kotleba, two out of 11 for SNS, one out of 11 for Most\u2013H\u00edd and one out of 10 for Network.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.volbysr.sk/en/data04.html|title=Order of candidates after taking into account preferential voting|publisher=Statistical Office of the Slovak Republic|accessdate=12 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n{|class=wikitable style=text-align:right\n|align=center colspan=7|[[File:Slovak National Council 2016.svg|350px]]\n|-\n!colspan=2|Party\n!Votes\n!%\n!Swing\n!Seats\n!+/\u2013\n|-\n|bgcolor={{Direction \u2013 Social Democracy/meta/color}}| ||align=left|[[Direction \u2013 Social Democracy]]||737,481||28.28||\u201316.13||49||\u201334\n|-\n|bgcolor={{Freedom and Solidarity/meta/color}}| ||align=left|[[Freedom and Solidarity]]||315,558||12.10||+6.22||21||+10\n|-\n|bgcolor=#6F654F| ||align=left|[[Ordinary People (Slovakia)|O\u013dANO\u2013NOVA]]||287,611||11.03||+2.48||19||+3\n|-\n|bgcolor={{Slovak National Party/meta/color}}| ||align=left|[[Slovak National Party]]||225,386||8.64||+4.09||15||+15\n|-\n|bgcolor={{Kotleba \u2013 People's Party Our Slovakia/meta/color}}| ||align=left|[[Kotleba \u2013 People's Party Our Slovakia]] (L'SNS)||209,779||8.04||+6.46||14||+14\n|-\n|bgcolor={{We Are Family (Slovakia)/meta/color}}| ||align=left|[[We Are Family (Slovakia)|We Are Family]]||172,860||6.63||New||11||New\n|-\n|bgcolor={{Most\u2013H\u00edd/meta/color}}| ||align=left|[[Most\u2013H\u00edd]]||169,593||6.50||\u20130.39||11||\u20132\n|-\n|bgcolor={{Slovak Conservative Party/meta/color}}| ||align=left|[[Slovak Conservative Party|Network]]||146,205||5.61||New||10||New\n|-\n|bgcolor=#FFE17C| ||align=left|[[Christian Democratic Movement]]||128,908||4.94||\u20133.88||0||\u201316\n|-\n|bgcolor={{Party of the Hungarian Community/meta/color}}| ||align=left|[[Party of the Hungarian Community]]||105,495||4.05||\u20130.23||0||0\n|-\n| ||align=left|Slovak Civic Coalition||21,785||0.84||New||0||New\n|-\n| ||align=left|TIP Party||18,845||0.72||New||0||New\n|-\n|bgcolor=green| ||align=left|[[Slovak Green Party]]||17,541||0.67||New||0||New\n|-\n|bgcolor={{Communist Party of Slovakia/meta/color}}| ||align=left|[[Communist Party of Slovakia]]||16,278||0.62||\u20130.10||0||0\n|-\n|bgcolor={{Slovak Democratic and Christian Union \u2013 Democratic Party/meta/color}}| ||align=left|[[Slovak Democratic and Christian Union \u2013 Democratic Party]]||6,938||0.27||\u20135.82||0||\u201311\n|-\n| ||align=left|CHANCE||6,522||0.25||New||0||New\n|-\n| ||align=left|Party of Modern Slovakia||4,559||0.17||New||0||New\n|-\n| ||align=left|Direct Democracy Party||3,595||0.14||New||0||New\n|-\n| ||align=left|Courage \u2013 Great National and Pro-Russian Coalition||3,428||0.13||New||0||New\n|-\n| ||align=left|[[Resistance \u2013 Labor Party]]||3,182||0.12||New||0||New\n|-\n| ||align=left|Hungarian Christian Democratic Alliance||2,426||0.09||New||0||New\n|-\n| ||align=left|Democratic Party - \u013dudo Kan\u00edk||1,998||0.08||New||0||New\n|-\n| ||align=left|Coalition \u2013 Together for Slovakia||1,777||0.07||New||0||New\n|-\n|colspan=2 align=left|Invalid/blank votes||20,798||\u2013||\u2013||\u2013||\u2013\n|-\n|colspan=2 align=left|'''Total'''||'''2,648,184'''||'''100'''||'''\u2013'''||'''150'''||'''0'''\n|-\n|colspan=2 align=left|Registered voters/turnout||4,426,760||59.82||+0.71||\u2013||\u2013\n|-\n|align=left colspan=7|Source: [https://web.archive.org/web/20160310083500/https://volbysr.sk/en/data03.html Volby]\n|}\n{{bar box\n| title=Popular vote\n| titlebar=#ddd\n| width=600px\n| barwidth=410px\n| bars=\n{{bar percent|SMER-SD|{{Direction \u2013 Social Democracy/meta/color}}|28.28}}\n{{bar percent|SaS|{{Freedom and Solidarity/meta/color}}|12.10}}\n{{bar percent|OL'aNO\u2013NOVA|{{Ordinary People (Slovakia)/meta/color}}|11.03}}\n{{bar percent|SNS|{{Slovak National Party/meta/color}}|8.64}}\n{{bar percent|L'SNS|{{People's Party \u2013 Our Slovakia/meta/color}}|8.04}}\n{{bar percent|SME RODINA|{{We Are Family (Slovakia)/meta/color}}|6.63}}\n{{bar percent|Most-H\u00edd|{{Most\u2013H\u00edd/meta/color}}|6.50}}\n{{bar percent|SIE\u0164|{{Network (Slovak party)/meta/color}}|5.61}}\n{{bar percent|KDH|{{Christian Democratic Movement/meta/color}}|4.94}}\n{{bar percent|SMK|{{Party of the Hungarian Coalition/meta/color}}|4.05}}\n{{bar percent|Other|#777777|8.09}}\n}}\n{{bar box\n| title=Parliamentary seats\n| titlebar=#ddd\n| width=600px\n| barwidth=410px\n| bars=\n{{bar percent|SMER-SD|{{Direction \u2013 Social Democracy/meta/color}}|32.67}}\n{{bar percent|SaS|{{Freedom and Solidarity/meta/color}}|14.00}}\n{{bar percent|OL'aNO\u2013NOVA|{{Ordinary People (Slovakia)/meta/color}}|12.67}}\n{{bar percent|SNS|{{Slovak National Party/meta/color}}|10.00}}\n{{bar percent|L'SNS|{{People's Party \u2013 Our Slovakia/meta/color}}|9.33}}\n{{bar percent|SME RODINA|{{We Are Family (Slovakia)/meta/color}}|7.33}}\n{{bar percent|Most-H\u00edd|{{Most\u2013H\u00edd/meta/color}}|7.33}}\n{{bar percent|SIE\u0164|{{Network (Slovak party)/meta/color}}|6.67}}\n}}\n\n==Government formation==\nOn 7 March, [[President of Slovakia]] [[Andrej Kiska]] invited each elected party, with the exception of \u013dSNS, for post-election talks. Fico was given the first opportunity by the President to form a stable coalition.<ref>{{cite news|title=President Kiska will authorise Fico to form government|url=http://spectator.sme.sk/c/20111933/president-kiska-will-authorise-fico-to-form-government.html|accessdate=9 March 2016|work=[[The Slovak Spectator]]|date=7 March 2016}}</ref> All parties, except We Are Family, had refused to discuss the possibility of going into government with \u013dSNS.<ref>{{cite news|title=Opinions on not inviting Kotleba differ|url=http://spectator.sme.sk/c/20113259/opinions-on-not-inviting-kotleba-differ.html|work=[[The Slovak Spectator]]|accessdate=9 March 2016|date=9 March 2016}}</ref> An [[anti-fascist]] protest was held the same day in Bratislava against \u013dSNS representation in parliament.<ref>{{cite news|title=People rallied in protest against Kotleba|url=http://spectator.sme.sk/c/20112473/people-rallied-in-protest-against-kotleba.html|accessdate=9 March 2016|work=[[The Slovak Spectator]]|date=8 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March, incumbent Fico informed president Andrej Kiska that he would form [[Fico's Third Cabinet|a four-party government coalition]], including Smer\u2013SD, the Slovak National Party, Most\u2013H\u00edd and Network,<ref>{{cite news|title=New Slovak Government and Posts|url=http://www.cas.sk/clanok/377287/robert-fico-oznamil-demisiu-vlady-a-prisiel-s-poriadnou-novinkou/|work=[[Nov\u00fd \u010cas]]|accessdate=17 March 2016|date=17 March 2016}}</ref> which together held 85 of the 150 seats.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://sites.google.com/site/marekhlavac/slovak_election_data_project Slovak Election Data Project]\n\n{{Slovak elections}}\n\n[[Category:Parliamentary elections in Slovakia]]\n[[Category:2016 elections in Europe|Slovakia]]\n[[Category:2016 in Slovakia]]\n[[Category:March 2016 events in Europe]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name = 2016 Slovak parliamentary election\n| country = Slovakia\n| type = parliamentary\n| ongoing = no\n| previous_election = 2012 Slovak parliamentary election\n| previous_year = 2012\n| next_election = 2020 Slovak parliamentary election\n| next_year = 2020\n| seats_for_election = All 150 seats in the [[National Council (Slovakia)|National Council]]\n| majority_seats = 76\n| election_date = 5 March 2016\n| turnout = 2,648,184 (59.82%)<br>{{increase}} 0.71 pp\n\n<!-- SMER-SD -->| image1 = [[File:Fico Juncker (