7|8.09}}\n}}\n{{bar box\n| title=Parliamentary seats\n| titlebar=#ddd\n| width=600px\n| barwidth=410px\n| bars=\n{{bar percent|SMER-SD|{{Direction \u2013 Social Democracy/meta/color}}|32.67}}\n{{bar percent|SaS|{{Freedom and Solidarity/meta/color}}|14.00}}\n{{bar percent|OL'aNO\u2013NOVA|{{Ordinary People (Slovakia)/meta/color}}|12.67}}\n{{bar percent|SNS|{{Slovak National Party/meta/color}}|10.00}}\n{{bar percent|L'SNS|{{People's Party \u2013 Our Slovakia/meta/color}}|9.33}}\n{{bar percent|SME RODINA|{{We Are Family (Slovakia)/meta/color}}|7.33}}\n{{bar percent|Most-H\u00edd|{{Most\u2013H\u00edd/meta/color}}|7.33}}\n{{bar percent|SIE\u0164|{{Network (Slovak party)/meta/color}}|6.67}}\n}}\n\n==Government formation==\nOn 7 March, [[President of Slovakia]] [[Andrej Kiska]] invited each elected party, with the exception of \u013dSNS, for post-election talks. Fico was given the first opportunity by the President to form a stable coalition.<ref>{{cite news|title=President Kiska will authorise Fico to form government|url=http://spectator.sme.sk/c/20111933/president-kiska-will-authorise-fico-to-form-government.html|accessdate=9 March 2016|work=[[The Slovak Spectator]]|date=7 March 2016}}</ref> All parties, except We Are Family, had refused to discuss the possibility of going into government with \u013dSNS.<ref>{{cite news|title=Opinions on not inviting Kotleba differ|url=http://spectator.sme.sk/c/20113259/opinions-on-not-inviting-kotleba-differ.html|work=[[The Slovak Spectator]]|accessdate=9 March 2016|date=9 March 2016}}</ref> An [[anti-fascist]] protest was held the same day in Bratislava against \u013dSNS representation in parliament.<ref>{{cite news|title=People rallied in protest against Kotleba|url=http://spectator.sme.sk/c/20112473/people-rallied-in-protest-against-kotleba.html|accessdate=9 March 2016|work=[[The Slovak Spectator]]|date=8 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March, incumbent Fico informed president Andrej Kiska that he would form [[Fico's Third Cabinet|a four-party government coalition]], including Smer\u2013SD, the Slovak National Party, Most\u2013H\u00edd and Network,<ref>{{cite news|title=New Slovak Government and Posts|url=http://www.cas.sk/clanok/377287/robert-fico-oznamil-demisiu-vlady-a-prisiel-s-poriadnou-novinkou/|work=[[Nov\u00fd \u010cas]]|accessdate=17 March 2016|date=17 March 2016}}</ref> which together held 85 of the 150 seats.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://sites.google.com/site/marekhlavac/slovak_election_data_project Slovak Election Data Project]\n\n{{Slovak elections}}\n\n[[Category:Parliamentary elections in Slovakia]]\n[[Category:2016 elections in Europe|Slovakia]]\n[[Category:2016 in Slovakia]]\n[[Category:March 2016 events in Europe]]\n", "name_user": "Alaney2k", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCampaign:the work's name is \"The New York Times\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2016_Slovak_parliamentary_election"}
{"title_page": "Making Our Dreams Come True", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Making Our Dreams Come True\n| cover      = Making_Our_Dreams_Come_True_-_Cyndi_Grecco.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Cyndi Grecco]]\n| album      = [[Making Our Dreams Come True (Cyndi Grecco album)|Making Our Dreams Come True]]\n| B-side     = Watching You\n| released   = May 1976\n| format     = [[Gramophone record|7\"]]\n| recorded   = 1976\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = Pop\n| length     = 2:29\n| label      = [[Private Stock Records]] 45086\n| writer     = [[Charles Fox (composer)|Charles Fox]], [[Norman Gimbel]]\n| producer   = [[Charles Fox (composer)|Charles Fox]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\n\"'''Making Our Dreams Come True'''\" is a 1976 hit single written by [[Charles Fox (composer)|Charles Fox]] and [[Norman Gimbel]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.allthelyrics.com/lyrics/televisiontv_theme_lyrics_soundtrack/making_our_dreams_come_true_by_norman_gimbel_and_charles |title=\"Making our Dreams Come True\" by Norman Gimbel and Charles Fox |website=allthelyrics.com |accessdate=January 17, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.45cat.com/record/psr45086 |title=Record Details |website=45cat.com |quote=(Fox-Gimbel) |accessdate=January 17, 2019}}</ref> It was recorded by [[Cyndi Grecco]], then an unknown musician.  It is the title track of [[Making Our Dreams Come True (Cyndi Grecco album)|her debut album]], used as the theme song to the television [[sitcom]] ''[[Laverne & Shirley]]''.\n\n\"Making Our Dreams Come True\" reached number 25 on the U.S. [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] and number 21 on the ''[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cash Box]]'' Top 100.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">''Joel Whitburn's Top Pop Singles 1955-1990'' - {{ISBN|0-89820-089-X}}</ref><ref name=\"tropicalglen1\">{{cite web |url=http://tropicalglen.com/Archives/70s_files/19760710.html |title=Cash Box Top 100 7/10/76 |website=Tropicalglen.com |date=1976-07-10 |accessdate=2016-10-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160322163706/http://tropicalglen.com/Archives/70s_files/19760710.html |archive-date=2016-03-22 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The song was a somewhat bigger hit in Canada, where it reached number 16.<ref name=\"bac-lac1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.4299a&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.4299a.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.4299a |title=Image : RPM Weekly - Library and Archives Canada |website=Bac-lac.gc.ca |date= |accessdate=2016-10-11}}</ref> It spent 16 weeks on the U.S. charts, peaking in early July,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/cyndi-grecco |title=Cyndi Grecco Chart History |website=billboard.com |accessdate=January 17, 2019}}</ref> and also reached number 13 on the [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Adult Contemporary chart]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/adult-contemporary/1976-07-04 |title=Billboard Adult Contemporary |date=July 4, 1976 |website=billboard.com |accessdate=January 17, 2019}}</ref> To date, it is Grecco's [[one-hit wonder|lone record to reach any chart]].\n\n==Chart performance==\n{{col-begin|width=65%}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1976)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n|Canadian ''RPM'' Top Singles<ref name=\"bac-lac1\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|16\n|-\n|U.S. ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Adult Contemporary]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|13\n|-\n|U.S. ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]]<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|25\n|-\n|U.S. ''[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cash Box]]'' Top 100<ref name=\"tropicalglen1\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|21\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\